Direct squad-level spend control in pay‑as‑you‑go setups can support durable adoption and richer workflows when budgets and reviews stay workflow‑portfolio‑centric and non‑punitive; it harms adoption when spend is experienced as a scarce, person‑blamed resource inside the squad.

Compared to centrally intermediated spend, direct control tends to help when:
- budgets are allocated to workflow portfolios, not individuals;
- exploration budgets are explicit and protected;
- cost feedback is coarse and outcome‑aware, and
- conflicts are arbitrated by simple norms (“in‑scope golden workflows are always OK”).

It tends to hurt when:
- the squad budget is small and undifferentiated (no exploration slice);
- cost reviews name people instead of workflows (“X used half the budget”);
- leaders respond to spikes with personal caps or freezes; and
- role or task norms are unclear, so every expensive run feels like a political bet.

Under those negative conditions, direct spend amplifies intra‑team tension, encourages run avoidance on complex work, and pushes serious tasks back to manual flows or private, untracked agent use. In more mature or higher‑trust teams that already use workflow‑portfolio budgeting and outcome‑aware reviews, direct spend can accelerate experimentation and local refinement without eroding trust.

Net: direct pay‑as‑you‑go control is not inherently better or worse than centralized spend; its effect on durable adoption depends on whether the team treats budget as a shared workflow portfolio resource with clear norms, or as a zero‑sum, person‑blamed token pool.
